@NODE Overview "About AGuideCheck"
The AGuideCheck program, or short the guide checker, parses an AmigaGuide
database file - thus a file like this manual - and checks it for possible
errors.


Amongst the things the guide checker looks at are:


- Illegal, unknown or broken commands

- Broken links, i.e. links to non-existing nodes.

- Nodes that have been defined but are never referenced.


As an additional feature, the guide checker may automatically create an
index node for the guide.


This version of the AGuide checker does now check for links across file
boundaries, i.e. links to external databases. It also identifies non-
AmigaGuide files and refuses (correctly) to check them.
Additionally, the index gets sorted, but the checker is not smart enough to
ignore words like "The", "A", "In", "About" etc. This means that you've most
likely to modify the index node a bit, or most nodes will end up sorted in
as 'T'. (-:

@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "Using AGuideCheck"
The AGuideCheck program must be called from the shell. It takes two
arguments, the name of the AmigaGuide file to check, and, optionally, the
name of an index file to create. The command template is, therefore:


@{I}
AGuideCheck FROM/A,INDEX,FMTCHECK/S,ALL/S
@{UI}


FROM            The file name of the database to check.


INDEX           The name of a file to write the index to.


FMTCHECK        If this keyword is given, AGuideCheck checks for possible
formatting problems of the SMARTWRAP command; I've often run into trouble if
a command was the last item on a line since the data on the next line is
directly attachted to the output of the command without any space.


ALL             Enter directories recursively if the FROM is a pattern.


The index file WILL NOT be created if the guide checker found any bugs.
Moreover, you might want to edit this file later on to improve the sorting
order - most nodes will end up sorted in as 'T' (or 'D' for german,
probably ;-) because the index creator is not yet smart enough to ignore
leading words as "The". You may also want to add addional entries to the
index. The complete index should then be concatenated with the file, a
reference to the index should be created and the resulting file should be
checked again for possible broken links.


Here an example, using this guide while still typing it:

@{CODE}
AGuideCheck GUIDES:AGuideCheck.guide

The output for the incomplete guide is now:


Problem found at line 229 : found unknown attribute.
\@\{DATA\}

Undefined node ERRORS referenced at line 32.
Node ME defined at line 197 is unreferenced.
Node TROUBLE defined at line 993 is unreferenced.
Node THANX defined at line 1140 is unreferenced.
@{BODY}


This means, the guide checker found the following problems:


- An unknown text attribute "DATA" has been found on line 229 of the file.
In this case, I should have typed \@BODY instead.


- A node named "ERRORS" on line 32 of the file that has been referenced, but
not (yet!) defined.


- Three nodes, defined at lines 197, 993 and 1140 respectively, are in fact
never referenced and therefore superflous.



If we try with another guide file, creating an index on the fly:


AGuideCheck GUIDES:BenchTrash.guide RAM:BenchTrash.index


runs without any problems and creates an index file in the RAM: disk which
looks, for this example, like this:

@{CODE}
\@NODE INDEX "Index"
\@\{CODE\}

        A...

        \@\{\"About BenchTrash" link OVERVIEW\}

... and so on.
@{BODY}


To include this file in your AmigaGuide data base, open this data base with
an editor of your choice, include the generated index file AT THE END of
the guide file and add a reference to the index at the beginning of the
guide like this, directly on top of the "MAIN" node:

@{CODE}
\@INDEX INDEX
\@NODE MAIN ....etc
@{BODY}

Save this document, and check it again for possible errors.


This "INDEX" command will now enable the "INDEX" button of the MultiView
window and show, well, the index.


A complete list of all error codes generated by the guide checker is here:


@{"List of error messages" link ERRORS}


@ENDNODE

@NODE ERRORS "Possible error messages"
Here's the list of possible error messages AGuideCheck may output. Please
note again that an index will not be created as long as there are still
errors.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
command not at start of line
@{UB}


AGuideCheck found a an \@ sign in the middle of the line that does not
introduce a text attribute, i.e. which is not followed by a opening brace
like {. The most common reason for this error message is by using the \@
sign in an EMail address like this:


thor\@math.tu-berlin.de

Future versions of the AmigaGuide system may interpret \@MATH as a possible
command and might be confused by this line. To avoid this error, "escape"
the \@ sign with a backslash \\, i.e. the text should look like this:


thor\\\@math.tu-berlin.de


The backslash itself will not be printed by MultiView and will not appear in
the output. The backslash itself can be inserted into the text by escaping
it with another backslash, i.e. with \\\\.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found illegal character
@{UB}


The guide checker found a character outside of the printable set of ASCII
characters, i.e. either an ASCII code below 0x20, or a code between 0x80 and
0x9f. These codes are reserved for ANSI control sequences and should be
avoided. They may confuse a printer if the document gets printed out.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found attribute open within attribute
@{UB}

The guide checker found an opening brace within an attribute description,
i.e. a string like \@{ foo{ bar LINK foo}. This is in most cases either a
typo, or a missing pair of double quotes, as in this example.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found double \@
@{UB}

The guide checker found a sequence of two at signs like \@\@. You most
likely did not want to start a command, but to print these literally. Use a
backslash to escape these characters, i.e. try \\\@\\\@ instead.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
command missing after introducer
@{UB}

The guide checker did not find a command behind the at sign. You most likely
forgot to escape the at-sign with a backslash, like \@ instead of \\\@.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found incomplete escape sequence
@{UB}

The guide checker found a single backslash \\ at the end of the line which
does not escape anything. You most likely wanted to insert a literal
backslash, but forgot to escape the backslash with an additional backslash,
i.e. used \\ instead of \\\\.

The backslash is used by the AmigaGuide as an escape character that avoids
interpretation of the next character as an AmigaGuide command. A special
AmigaGuide command is the backslash itself, which has to be escaped for that
reason - with another backslash, of course.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found unterminated string
@{UB}

The guide checker found a string opening with a double quote on the line
without finding the closing double quote on the same line.


Double quotes have a special meaning within text attributes, as for example
for the LINK attribute - they keep strings with spaces together and avoid
interpretation of the characters, especially blank spaces, within the
quotes.


The most common reason for this error code is that you used an editor with
automatic word wrapping which broke the line in the middle of the string.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found unterminated attribute
@{UB}

The checker found an attribute open brace { without finding the matching
attribute close brace } on the same line. AmigaGuide attributes MUST fit on
a single line and cannot be broken into several lines.


The most common reason is that your text editor uses automatic word wrapping
and broke the input line within the middle of the attribute.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found attribute outside a node
@{UB}

The guide checker found an attribute outside of a \@NODE \@ENDNODE pair.
This does not make any sense because this attribute will never be used.

You most likely forgot a \@NODE.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found obsolete ALINK command
@{UB}

The ALINK command is obsolete and should not be used anymore. Replace it
by the LINK command.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found obsolete CLOSE command
@{UB}

Please do not use the CLOSE command, this is no longer supported and
obsolete.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found obsolete QUIT command
@{UB}

The QUIT command should not be used in newer AmigaGuide documents, it is
documented as obsolete.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found unknown attribute
@{UB}

The guide checker found a text attribute it does not know. I tried my best
to keep the list of valid attributes up to date, so that is most likely a
typo.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
name parameter missing
@{UB}

The guide checker found a command that requires a name parameter without
that parameter, e.g. a \@NODE command without the name of the node or an
\@INDEX command without the name of the index node.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found \@NODE inside a node
@{UB}

The guide checker found another \@NODE command within an AmigaGuide node.
You most likely forgot to end the node properly with an \@ENDNODE command.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found \@ENDNODE outside a node
@{UB}

The guide checker found an \@ENDNODE command outside of a valid AmigaGuide
node. You most likely forgot a \@NODE somewhere above.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found \@$VER inside a node
@{UB}

A \@$VER command was found inside a node. This command is only available
outside of any nodes, and should be put to the beginning of the database.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found (C) inside a node
@{UB}

The checker found a \@(C) copyright notice command within a node. This
command is only available outside of nodes.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found AUTHOR inside a node
@{UB}

The checker found an \@AUTOR command within a node. This command is only
available outside of nodes, and should go to the beginning of the database.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found DATABASE inside a node
@{UB}

The guide checker found a \@DATABASE command within a node, which is
illegal. This command should be the very first line of an AmigaGuide
document and not anywhere else.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found DATABASE not at start of file
@{UB}

The checker found a \@DATABASE command at some other position than the first
line of the file. This command MUST be the very first command of an
AmigaGuide database, as it is used by MultiView for identification.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found DNODE inside a node
@{UB}

A \@DNODE command was found within a node. The DNODE command was used to
introduce a node maintained by a dynamic node host, but is not a command
that can be used within a node itself.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found obsolete DNODE command
@{UB}

The \@DNODE command is obsolete and should no longer be used. A standard
\@NODE is good enough to read a node from a dynamic node host.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found HEIGHT inside a node
@{UB}

The \@HEIGHT command should not be used within nodes. It only makes sense in
the header of the AmigaGuide database.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found MASTER inside a node
@{UB}

The \@MASTER command was found inside a node where it should not go. Place
it in the header of the AmigaGuide file.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found TAB inside a node
@{UB}

The \@TAB command was found within a node. However, the TAB settings cannot
be changed within the node.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found WIDTH inside a node
@{UB}

The \@WIDHT command makes not any sense within a node. Please move it to the
header of the Database.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found KEYWORDS outside a node
@{UB}

A \@KEYWORDS command was found outside of a node where it does not make any
sense. You might have forgotten a \@NODE command as well.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found NEXT outside a node
@{UB}

A \@NEXT command was found outside of a valid node. Since this command links
the current node to a next one, this does not make any sense. Please move
this command into a node, or insert a \@NODE command on top of it you might
have forgotten.

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found PREV outside a node
@{UB}

A \@PREV command, linking nodes together, was found outside of a node.

_______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found TOC outside a node
@{UB}

You tried to select the table of contents without giving a node this is
relative to. The \@TOC command must go into a node to have any effect.

_______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found TITLE outside a node
@{UB}

You tried to change the window title of a node outside of any node structure
this command is relative to. You might have forgotten a \@NODE command
somewhere above.

_______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
found unknown command
@{UB}

The guide checker found a command it does not know. Since I tried to keep
this program up to date, this is most likely a typo.

_______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
Undefined node ... referenced at line ...
@{UB}

A \@LINK command referred to a node that does not exist in the database
file. You either forgot to create this node, or you spelled the name of an
existing node in the wrong way.


@{B}Warning: This version of AGuideCheck does not support links to nodes of
external database files. If the node referred to is given by a file name,
this is an indicator that you should not check the given database by this
version of the guide checker.
@{UB}

______________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
Node ... defined at line ... is unreferenced.
@{UB}

You defined a node within an AmigaGuide database which is never used within
that database, i.e. the user will never see it. You may remove this node
quietly without any change.

You most likely forgot to dereference this node somewhere in the document.


@{B}Warning: Since this version of AGuideCheck does not yet handle links to
and from external databases, it might also be that - even this node is not
dereferenced by the checked file - it is dereferenced by some external
file.@{UB}



You should check carefully if the file you checked is really supposed to be
a one-file database, and if it's not, avoid to check it with this program.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
Node ... defined at line ... has no title.
@{UB}

You defined a node at the printed line which does not have any title. While
this is not illegal, it is at least confusing to the user. Even worse, this
node may not appear in the index.

You most likely forgot to add a title behind the \@NODE command.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
command at end of previous line, expect formatting errors.
@{UB}

This is only printed if the FMTCHECK command line option was given. The
AGuideCheck found a command as the last item of a line within the \@BODY
with \@SMARTWRAP enabled. This means that the AmigaGuide library does not
insert a space to the beginning of the next line, unlike what you might
expect. The resulting layout may look rather poor due to this missing space.

_____________________________________________________________________________

@{B}
duplicate node found
@{UB}

The AGuideCheck program found a \@NODE command defining a node that was
already defined.

@ENDNODE
@NODE history "The history of AGuideCheck"
Version 2.00:

First version, supposed to replace the BadLinks program which throws just
too many enforcer hits. Used in private only.


Version 2.03:

First AmiNet release.


Version 2.04:

Added the FMTCHECK option, added checks for duplicate nodes.


Version 2.06:

Added partial support for external nodes. AGuideCheck will print a warning
if it finds some, but it won't follow them yet.


Version 2.10:

Added full support for external references. Cross references are
now checked fully. Fixed several flaws in the line parser concerning the use
of \@ and the escape-character \\ in quoted strings. Added pattern matching
support.

@ENDNODE

